		<description><![CDATA[<p>Today, I'm going to show you a little chromatic bass lick that's often used to link up chord tones / phrases. If you haven't watched my lesson called Chord Tones / One Position Exercise, do check it out too! As...</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/target-chord-tones-chromatically.html">How to Target Chord Tones Chromatically (L#21)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Today, I'm going to show you a little chromatic bass lick that's often used to link up chord tones / phrases. If you haven't watched my lesson called <a title="Chord Tones Exercice" href="http://scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/chord-tones-bass-exercise.html">Chord Tones / One Position Exercise</a>, do check it out too!</p>
<p>As you probably know by now, I'm not particularly in favour of learning a ton of licks and trying to use them everytime it seems to 'fit in'. I think it's much more profitable to spend a reasonable amount of time figuring out 'how music works'. That's how you'll really become a better and more versatile musician, and you'll be able to play different styles of music with different people, get more gigs, etc.</p>
<p>That said, I'm not fiercely 'anti-licks' either! Not at all. They definitely have their place in your practice and knowing a variety of bass licks comes in very handy in many situations.</p>
<p>This is the case of the chromatic lick I'm showing you in this lesson, that allows you to target chord tones --link chords… chromatically. Very simple, very useful! Ready? Go!</p>
<p><div><a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-academy" class="post_cta">Full tab/notation & workbook available to Academy members &raquo;</a></div><div class="video_wrap "><iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/CASblh-d_4s" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div><br />
</p>
